sentences: Lisa Simeone (born July 11, 1957) is an American freelance radio host and writer.
She attended St. John's College in Annapolis, Maryland, where she graduated in 1980 with a bachelor's degree in liberal arts.
Later on, studying at the Writing Seminars at Johns Hopkins University, she received a master's degree in 1997.

In 1996, after ten years at WJHU, where her programming included classical, folk, and jazz music, plus a wide variety of reports, interviews, and call-in programs on intriguing topics, she left to pursue a graduate degree in writing.
From 1998 to 2000, she was a regular host of NPR's Performance Today and Weekend Edition Sunday.
She became full-time host of NPR's Weekend All Things Considered in 2000.
She left the show in March 2002 to return to freelancing, and shortly afterwards began hosting NPR's World of Opera.
In 2007, she also began hosting the weekly Chicago Symphony Orchestra broadcast series, produced and syndicated by the Chicago radio service WFMT.
In October 2011, Simeone became involved in the Occupy movement.
Because of this activity, she was fired from Soundprint on October 19, 2011.
Simeone remained as host until the show ended in 2016.

Simeone, who lives in Baltimore, said she has been serving with about 50 people on a steering committee for an occupation protest on Pennsylvania Avenue [in Washington, D.C.] that's known as the October 2011 Movement.

In 1996, after ten years at WJHU, where her programming included classical, folk, and jazz music, plus a wide variety of reports, interviews, and call-in programs on intriguing topics, she left to pursue a graduate degree in writing.
From 1998 to 2000, she was a regular host of NPR's Performance Today and Weekend Edition Sunday.
She became full-time host of NPR's Weekend All Things Considered in 2000.
She also returned to hosting and writing for the independent radio documentary series Soundprint, which she had done before she was hired at Weekend All Things Considered.
Simeone has written for the Baltimore City Paper, The Urbanite, and The Baltimore Sun, and is the beauty editor and a columnist at Baltimore Style.
